data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 with no migration needed.

**No Thread.Abort migration is required here.**

That said, for .NET 8 you'd likely want to modernize this to use `Task`/`Parallel` instead of raw threads:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Delay(100, ct);
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` (the cooperative replacement for `Thread.Abort`) should you need it later.
